\brief Function to enable the selectedAtbX on the current IP module that wants to make use of the selectedAtbX. This function needs to perform 2 SPI reads and 2 SPI writes. \details This function needs as inputs the bit fields of the ATB at register 0xA00 since these can vary from one IP to another. In that case, the function stores those from the IP that wants to connect to ATB, so that it can disconnected that IP if a newer one is asked to connect to the ATB in the same selectedAtbX. \param [in] ipToConnect : struct containing the parameters of the IP to connect being those \param [in] atbCtlCounterValue: value to be set in the ATB counter before breaking ATB usage from connected IP, by default is set to 0x0f \param [in] atbCtlSelValue: ATBx_SEL register value to indicating the node of the IP to be connected to the selectedAtbX. If not used keep it set to 0x00u \param [in] selectedAtbX: ATB to be enabled for the IP module \param [in] modeOfOperation: variable to select what is the mode of operation for the selected IP \param [in/out] RFE_ERROR_FUNCTION_PARAMETER

\brief This function will disconnect the usage of the selectedAtbX from the IP id specified in previousIdModule. This function will use SPI to access IP ATB setting register( 0xA00 ) and disconnect ATB from it. \param [in] selectedAtbX: ATB to be disconnected \param [in/out] RFE_ERROR_FUNCTION_PARAMETER

\brief Function that enables switches in the ATB unit depending on the selected input of the ATB. If the selected input does not match the expected mode of operation for the ATB set via the initialisation function, this function will throw an error and it will not enable the switches within the ATB \param [in] selectedAtbX: ATB where the specified input is going to be enabled. \param [in] atbXInputSource: ATB input that is going to be use as source of signal to the selectedAtbX \param [in] enable: flag to enable ( true ) or disable ( false ) the input to the selectedAtbX. \param [in/out] RFE_ERROR_FUNCTION_PARAMETER

\brief Function to select what ground to be used on the ATB ADC only when working in single mode. The function performs a check on that, throwing an error if not set the single mode This function does not make use of SPI read/writes it just modifies the input configuration registers(atbAdcInputMux) accordingly to configure ADC ground in single mode. The caller of this function is rfeHwAtb_ctrlAtbAdcInputSingleModeSetter(). \details ATB HW allows the configuration of the ATB ADC ground via MUX_VNEG_SE multiplexer, this function enables this functionality. Thus this function will rely on having defined previously the ATB ADC to work in single mode, via rfeHwAtb_ctrlAtbAdcInputSingleModeSetter(); in that case this function checks what selectedAtbX needs to configure and it sets the ground to be set in the ADC via the MUX_VNEG_SE. The grounding mapping can be found in ATB SW Unit ConfigurationvX.pptx tab Pinout-Single-End-Grounding. \param [in] selectedAtbX: ATB where the ADC will be configured \param [in] adcSingleModeGround: variable indicating the ground to be used by the ATB ADC single-ending mode. \param [in] pAtbAdcInputMux: register that holds all muxers ( MUX_P/N and MUX_VNEG_SE ) configuration and that will be modified accordingly to ADC_SEL \param [in/out] RFE_ERROR_FUNCTION_PARAMETER \return updated atbAdcInputMux with the configured ground for single mode

\brief Function that sets whether the ADC is going to be configured as differential-ended or singled-ended, what inputs are connected to the ATB ADC via (ADC_SEL register), and sets ADC input gain mode (normal or div2). This function does make use of SPI read to access HW registers, therefore it will provide the read register to the functions that set them up and afterwards it will write the new register via SPI. \details The function will set the ADC mode in differential or single ended via dedicated functionality which are exclusive to avoid misconfiguration. \param [in] selectedAtbX: ATB to be enabled for the IP module \param [in] adcInputSel: variable indicating the input to be set in ATB ADC ( this variable controls directly ADC_SEL ) \param [in] adcEndToSet: variable indicating how to configure the ATB ADC end, differential-ended or signled-ended \param [in] adcSingleModeGround : variable indicating the ground to be used by the ATB ADC in single-ended mode. If differential-ended mode is chosen, this variable is ignored \param [in] adcGainMode : adc input gain mode (i.e. normal or div2) \param [in/out] RFE_ERROR_FUNCTION_PARAMETER

\brief Function to disable pull down lines based on input to be used in ATB \param [in] atbXInputSource: ATBxMaser input where the pull down lines should be disabled \param [in] disablePullDown: flag to control whether we disable the pullDown lines(true) or not (false) \param [in/out] RFE_ERROR_FUNCTION_PARAMETER

\brief Function to directly change whether the ADC working in MONO mode or CONT Mode, changing the ADC mode will update the stored samples to average to 1 sample in case MONO mode is enabled. This function can be used to disable the CONT mode where ADC CLK is being generated by setting the mode to MONO \param [in] selectedAtbX: ATB whose ADC is going to be configured \param [in] adcSamplingRate: ATB ADC sampling rate value \param [in] adcDutyCycle: ATB ADC Duty cycle value \param [in] adcAveragedEnabled: Enabling ATB ADc averaging or not \param [in] adcAveragingMode: ATB ADC averaging mode to be configured \param [in] adcSamplesToAverage: ATB ADC number of samples to average to configure \param [in/out] RFE_ERROR_FUNCTION_PARAMETER

\brief Function to directly change whether the ADC working in MONO mode or CONT Mode, changing the ADC mode will update the stored samples to average to 1 sample in case MONO mode is enabled. Notice that this function make use of SPI read and writes \details This function can be used to enable or disable the CONT mode where ADC CLK is being generated by setting RFE_HW_ATB_ADC_CTL_FUNC_ADC1/2_CONT_MONO_BIT. In case that the CONT mode is set, the function will set to the averaging bit ( RFE_HW_ATB_ADC_CTL_FUNC_ADC1/2_AVE_EN_BIT ) needed by the CONT mode, and it be will cleared if the MONO mode is set. \attention When setting the ATB ADC gain in DIV2 mode, the Duty Cycle has to be set to 75%, this will be automatically enforced by this function. \param [in] selectedAtbX: ATB whose ADC is configured as Mode MONO or CONT and where we need to enable averaging or not \param [in] adcMode: ATB ADC mode to be set \param [in/out] RFE_ERROR_FUNCTION_PARAMETER

\brief Function to trigger data acquisition via selectedAtbX ADC using continuous mode of the selectedAtbX ADC. This function will perform an SPI read and SPI write via internal call \details This function relies on having configured in advance the ADC via the usage of rfeHwAtb_ctrlAtbAdcBasicSettingsSetter(), therefore, sampling rate, number of samples to use, averaging mode and duty cycle are NOT set by this function. In order to ensure that the ADC is configured, it checks that ATB mode of operation and the averaging mode are set, if they are not set the function will trigger an error and not acquisition will be triggered. \param [in] selectedAtbX: ATB whose ADC is going to be configured \param [in] startSampling: flag to start ( true ) or stop ( false ) acquiring data via the ADC. By setting it to false we effectively change the ADC mode of operation to MONO stopping the acquisition. \param [in/out] RFE_ERROR_FUNCTION_PARAMETER

\brief Function to trigger data acquisition in selectedAtbX ADC using mono mode. This function will perform an SPI read and SPI write via internal call \details This function relies on having configured in advance the ADC via the usage of rfeHwAtb_ctrlAtbAdcBasicSettingsSetter(), therefore, sampling rate, number of samples to use, averaging mode and duty cycle are NOT set by this function. In order to ensure that the ADC is configured it checks that ATB mode of operation and the averaging mode are set, if they are not set the function will trigger an error and not acquisition will be triggered. Also the function is capable to block itself the required amount of time in MONO mode, to perform the ADC acquisition based on the configured sampling time and number of samples to average, in case the caller is not capable of. In this way, we try to ensure that the register will contain the correct amount of samples. In order to enable this feature the flag enableWaitForSamples should be turned on. \param [in] selectedAtbX: ATB whose ADC is going to be configured \param [in] enableWaitForSamples: flag that tells the function whether enabling internal wait loop (true) or not (false) \param [in/out] RFE_ERROR_FUNCTION_PARAMETER

\brief Function to collect the sample from the selectedAtbX ADC either in mono or continuous mode and return it back. This function will perform an SPI read and SPI write via internal call \details The function checks that the selectedAtbX ATB has an operation mode set and that ADC is configured in average mode prior to invoking the function to read from registers, if the ADC is not configured properly an error is thrown. The way of configuring the selectedAtbX ADC is first via rfeHwAtb_ctrlAtbAdcBasicSettingsSetter() and secondly via rfeHwAtb_ctrlAtbAdcAverageModeSetter(). \attention This function will return the raw ADC data from register, without any trimming applied into it. \param [in] selectedAtbX: ATB where the ADC has been triggered to sample \param [in/out] RFE_ERROR_FUNCTION_PARAMETER \return: rfeHwSpi_register32_t containing the sample. In case of error this value is set to an invalid value 0xFFFFFFFFul because all ADC samples are 12bits based

\brief Function to set up ATB bandgap and use its default voltage of 0V, this function relies on checking ATB HW flag,RFE_HW_ATB_BG_STATUS_BG_OK_FLAG_BIT, that indicates the proper powering up of the ATB. In case the bandgap cannot be powered up, the function will throw an error since this is essential for ATB proper working. This Function make use of SPI transactions \details In order to Power On ATB the general steps are illustrated below. Steps 1,2 and 3 are being performed within rfeHwAtb_ctrlAtbPowerOn(): 1. Read PON register config and BandGap register config. TODO, if this step were handled in the Power Manager it should be removed from this function 2. Enable Level shifters . TODO,if this step were handled in the Power Manager it should be removed from this function 3. Enable ADC Level shifters. TODO,if this step were handled in the Power Manager it should be removed from this function The steps are being performed within this function: 4. Enable BandGap, set standard operation configuration bits, set BandGap to default value, 0V , and disable BandGap RC filter 5. Wait till BandGap flag is acknowledged 6. Re-enable BandGap RC filter \param [in] enable variable that enables the bandgap in default mode or not \param [in/out] RFE_ERROR_FUNCTION_PARAMETER

\brief Function to enable or disable the ADC associated to the ATBXMAster bus. \param [in] selectedAtbX: ATB where ADC is going to be enabled/disabled \param [in] powerOn: flag to enable (true) or disable(false) the ADC \param [in/out] RFE_ERROR_FUNCTION_PARAMETER

\brief Setter function for ATB ADC internal gain error correction factor \details Setter function for ATB ADC internal gain error correction factor Div2 and Normal gain mode require dedicated gain and offset error correction factors \param [in] selectedAtbX: variable indicating which ATB ADC to be updated (1 or 2) \param [in] adcEndMode: enum indicating single-ended vs differential mode \param [in] gainMode: enum indicating gain mode of ATB ADC corresponding to input gain correction factor \param [in] gainFactor: gain factor (e.g. as the result of calibration routine) \param [in/out] RFE_ERROR_FUNCTION_PARAMETER

\brief Setter function for ATB ADC internal offset error correction factor \details Setter function for ATB ADC internal offset error correction factor Div2 and Normal gain mode require dedicated gain and offset error correction factors \param [in] selectedAtbX: variable indicating the ATB ADC to be updated (1 or 2) \param [in] adcEndMode: enum indicating single-ended vs differential mode \param [in] gainMode: enum indicating gain mode of ATB ADC corresponding to input offset correction factor \param [in] offsetFactor: offset factor (e.g. as the result of calibration routine) \param [in/out] RFE_ERROR_FUNCTION_PARAMETER

\brief Getter function for ATB ADC internal gain error correction factor \details Getter function for ATB ADC internal gain error correction factor Div2 and Normal gain mode have dedicated gain and offset error correction factors \param [in] selectedAtbX: variable indicating the ATB ADC of interest \param [in] adcEndMode: enum indicating single-ended vs differential mode \param [in] gainMode: enum indicating gain mode of ATB ADC \param [in/out] RFE_ERROR_FUNCTION_PARAMETER \return gain factor of given ATB ADC for a given gain mode

\brief Getter function for ATB ADC internal offset error correction factor \details Getter function for ATB ADC internal offset error correction factor Div2 and Normal gain mode have dedicated gain and offset error correction factors \param [in] selectedAtbX: variable indicating the ATB ADC of interest \param [in] adcEndMode: enum indicating single-ended vs differential mode \param [in] gainMode: enum indicating gain mode of ATB ADC \param [in/out] RFE_ERROR_FUNCTION_PARAMETER \return offset factor of given ATB ADC for a given gain mode

\brief Function that converts ATB ADC sample code into corresponding voltage in mV \details Function that converts ATB ADC sample code into corresponding voltage in mV Function applies gain and offset error correction factors (e.g. as the result of calibration) \param [in] code: ATB ADC sample code \param [in] selectedAtbX: variable indicating which ADC to use ATB ADC1 or ATB ADC2 \param [in] adcEndMode: enum indicating single-ended vs differential mode \param [in] adcGainMode: enum indicating normal vs div2 gain mode \param [in/out] RFE_ERROR_FUNCTION_PARAMETER \return float voltage [mV] in float format corresponding to input sample code

\brief Function that converts ATB ADC input voltage in mV into ATB ADC sample code \details Function that converts ATB ADC input voltage in mV into correspond ATB ADC sample code Function applies gain and offset error correction factors (e.g. as the result of calibration or trimming) \attention This function will return the corrected ATB ADC data associated to the input voltage, if real raw ADC data without any correction is required set showRawAdcValue to true. \param [in] voltage: ATB ADC input voltage \param [in] selectedAtbX: variable indicating which ADC to use ATB ADC1 or ATB ADC2 \param [in] adcEndMode: enum indicating single-ended vs differential mode \param [in] adcGainMode: enum indicating normal vs div2 gain mode \param [in] showRawAdcValue: boolean indicating whether returning the trimmed ATB ADC value ( false ) or associated raw ATB ADC value ( true ) where trimming corrections have been removed. \param [in/out] RFE_ERROR_FUNCTION_PARAMETER \return uint32_t ADC sample code in uint16_t corresponding to input voltage
\brief Function intended to change state in ATB from Off to Standby This function make use of 4SPI transactions \details see rfeHwAtb_ctrlAtbPowerOn() \param RFE_ERROR_FUNCTION_PARAMETER
\brief Function intended to change state in ATB from Standby to On This function make use of 8SPI transactions \param RFE_ERROR_FUNCTION_PARAMETER
\brief Function intended to change state in ATB from On to Standby This function make use of 5SPI transactions \param RFE_ERROR_FUNCTION_PARAMETER
\brief This function is intended to change state in ATB from Standby to On This function make use of 3SPI transactions \param RFE_ERROR_FUNCTION_PARAMETER

\brief Function intended to enable on or off ATB and ATB ADCs PONs This function make use of 2SPI transactions \details In order to Power On ATB the general steps are illustrated below. These steps are being performed within rfeHwAtb_ctrlAtbPowerOn() -> 2SPI 1. Read PON register config and BandGap register config. 2. Enable Level shifters . 3. Enable ADC Level shifters. The steps are being performed within rfeHwAtb_ctrlAtbBandGapDefaultMode -> 3SPI 4. Enable BandGap, set standard operation configuration bits, set BandGap to default value, 0V , and disable BandGap RC filter 5. Wait till BandGap flag is acknowledged 6. Re-enable BandGap RC filter \param [in] enable variable to indicate whether the PONs are on or off \param [in\out] RFE_ERROR_FUNCTION_PARAMETER

\brief Function intended to set the level shifters for the ATB ADCs This function make use of 2SPI(only one ATB ADC configured) or 3SPI transactions( both ATB ADC configured) \param [in] selectedAtbX variable holding the ADC to be configured \param [in\out] RFE_ERROR_FUNCTION_PARAMETER

\brief Function dedicated to enable the cross-switch from one ATB (source ATB) to the other (destination ATB) \details This function will enable the switch to route input from source ATBx towards destination ATBx ( enabling cross-switch ). On the source ATB it enables ADC_TO_EXT switch, whereas on destination ATB, the function enables the input towards ATB (via switch ADC_TO_DC) \attention This function does not enable 1. ATB source input: external/internal source must be set via rfeHwAtb_ctrlAtbSetterInputSource(), this done in this way to minimise a voltage increase in if the unit is not set in the right mode of operation. Function has got preconditions since this functionality involves using counter path ATB 1. The function checks whether destination ATB is being used (it has been connected to another IP), if that is the case the function will avoid cross-switch mode and throw an error (rfe_error_atbCrossSwitchNotEnabled_e) 2. The function checks for the correct atb configured sources. The only supported sources for croos-switching are external current (rfeHwAtb_atbSource_ext_current_e) or DC internal current (rfeHwAtb_atbSource_dc1_intCurrent_e), any other configured source will trigger an error (rfe_error_atbCrossSwitchNotEnabled_e) \param [in] atbInitiatingCrossSwitch: variable holding what ATB is starting the cross-switch. The ATB here specified is the source of the signal to be routed to the counter part ATB (destination ATB) \param [in] enable: variable indicating whether enabling the cross-switch (true) or not (false). Disabling it, does disable the cross-switch in source ATB and voltage input on destination ATB, thus this variable can be used to disable this whole functionality. \param [in/out] RFE_ERROR_FUNCTION_PARAMETER

\brief Function to enabling trimming resistors and set their correspondent values \param [in] selectedAtbX: ATB where trimming resistors are being enabled \param [in] atbResistorToSet: selected resistor to change its value \param [in] adcDcTrimRes0Value : value to set for Res0 in ATBXMaster \param [in] adcDcTrimRes1Value : value to set for Res0 in ATBXMaster \param [in/out] RFE_ERROR_FUNCTION_PARAMETER

\brief Function to enable or disable the set of trimming resistors at the input of ATB ADC. \detail This function only enables the trimming resistors associated to the ATB ADC input, those are RESx_TO_ADC. \param [in] selectedAtbX: ATB where trimming resistors are being enabled \param [in] atbADCResistorToEnable: selected trimming resistor to be enabled or disabled as input towards ADC \param [in] enable: flag to enable the resistor ( true ) or disable it( false ) \param [in/out] RFE_ERROR_FUNCTION_PARAMETER

\brief Function to enable or disable on ATB DC bus path/node to the trimming resistors either if current comes from internal DC bus or is provided on external pins \details This function is aimed to enable the ATB DC switches for current measurement.Based on the ATB DC source selected via rfeHwAtb_ctrlAtbDcInputSourceSetter, this function allows to configure following ATB DC switches: 1. ATB DC source is set to rfeHwAtb_atbSource_ext_current_e: in this case the function will enable/disable RESxTO_DC switches from ATB DC bus. 2. ATB DC source is set to rfeHwAtb_atbSource_dc1_intCurrent_e: in this case the function will enable/disable INOUT_TO_RESx switches from ATB DC bus. \attention This function does not enable RESx_TO_ADC, to enable those please use rfeHwAtb_ctrlAtbTrimmingResistorsEnable \param [in] selectedAtbX: ATB where RESx_TO_DC switches are being enabled \param [in] atbResistorNodeToEnable selected switch controlling the node to be enabled \param [in] enable: flag to enable the switch ( true ) or disable it( false ) \param [in/out] RFE_ERROR_FUNCTION_PARAMETER

\brief Function intended to enable ATB 0.9V LDO for RF Buffer and 1.35 LDO's for AC functionality. This function make usage of 4SPI transactions \details Depending on what signal wants to be routed out from RF Buffer, the correct voltage to LDO0V9 will have to be provided. At the time being three situations have been identified 1. CHIRP PLL with -8dBm amplitude at PLL TEST pin -> ldoRfBufferVoltage = 1V -> enableLDO1V35 = false 2. MCGEN signal at PLL TEST pin -> ldoRfBufferVoltage = 0.9V -> enableLDO1V35 = false 3. AC ATB bus -> ldoRfBufferVoltage = 0.9V -> enableLDO1V35 = true Notice that while working only with RF Buffer enableLDO1V35 should be false and when working with ATB AC bus enableLDO1V35 should be true. \attention This function will disable LDO1V35 internally if 1V is requested to LDO0V9 on RF Buffer. This is done to prevent a misconfiguration of ATB LDO's \param [in] ldoRfBufferVoltage variable indicating what voltage to be set in the LDO0V9 for RF Buffer \param [in] enableLDO1V35 variable to indicate whether enabling ( true ) or not ( false ) the LDO1V35, it should be enabled when working with AC ATB bus, see details. \param [in/out] RFE_ERROR_FUNCTION_PARAMETER - Error handling parameter: On success rfe_error_none_e is returned

\brief Function intended to route the ATB RF Buffer output to be accessible on output pin PLL TEST. This function uses 4SPI transactions \attention This function requires a previous call to 1. rfeHwAtb_ctrlAtbRFLDOSetter() so that 0.9V LDO in RF Buffer is active 2. rfeHwAtb_ctrlAtbPullDownLinesSetter() so that AC lines are not grounded \param [in] signalToPLLTestPin variable indicating what RF signal to be forwarded from RF Buffer towards PLL TEST pin \param [in] signalOutputPower variable indicating the output power for the RF signal to be forwarded from RF Buffer towards PLL TEST pin. Notice that if signalToPLLTestPin is rfeHwAtb_rfSignalToPLLTest_none_e the output power is set to minimum. \param [in/out] RFE_ERROR_FUNCTION_PARAMETER - Error handling parameter: On success rfe_error_none_e is returned

\brief Function to initialise the ATB into the right mode of operation depending on what functionality needs to be enabled. This function indicates the ATB initialisation for the different modes in which ATB can work \details The foreseen mode of operations are the following Not set : ATB is has all switches disabled IP DC usage: ATB is configured to route DC input into ATB-ADC IP AC usage: ATB is configured to route AC input into ATB-ADC External Voltage Trimming: ATB is configured to route its external voltage source( on OTP port ) as input to ATB1Master, into ATB1Master ADC, and via cross-talking into other ATB2Master ADC as well as ATB2Master external output ( OTP ) External Current Trimming: ATB is configure to route its external current source ( on OTP port ) as input to ATB1Master ADC. This mode shall enable the Trimming resistor to convert current input into voltage to be measured by the ADC. Internal Current Trimming: ATB is configure to route its internal current source ( on DC port ) as input to ATB1Master ADC. This mode shall enable the Trimming resistor to convert current input into voltage to be measured by the ADC. \param [in] ipToConnect: struct containing the parameters of the IP to connect being those \param [in] atbCtlCounterValue: value to be set in the counter \param [in] modeOfOperation: variable to select what is the mode of operation for the selected IP \param [in] selectedAtbX: ATB to be enabled for the IP module \param [in] adcSamplingRate: ATB ADC sampling rate value \param [in] adcAveragingMode: ATB ADC averaging mode to be configured \param [in] adcAveragedEnabled: Enabling ATB ADc averaging or not \param [in] adcSamplesToAverage: ATB ADC number of samples to average to configure \param [in/out] RFE_ERROR_FUNCTION_PARAMETER
\brief Function to reset the selectedAtbX. TODO: implement this whether Validation requires or DfT \param [in] selectedAtbX : ATB to be reset \param [in/out] RFE_ERROR_FUNCTION_PARAMETER

\brief This function is intended to enable or disable the ATB AC IF Buffer, it also enabled to attenuate the IF filter gain or not. This function make use of SPI transactions and consumes 2SPI \details ATB AC buffer gain is kept to its default value of 0 Notice that this function also set the mode of operation of ATB to AC usage \param [in] selectedAtbX: variable indicating which AC IF Buffer ATB bus to configure. rfeHwAtb_atbMaster_1_e selects AC1 IF Buffer ATB rfeHwAtb_atbMaster_2_e selects AC2 IF Buffer ATB \param [in] enableIFBuffer: variable to enable (true) or disable (false) the AC IF Buffer on ATB \param [in] attenuateIFBuffGain: variable to attenuate (true) or not (false) the gain on AC IF Buffer on ATB. Recommended settings is not to attenuate the gain (false). \param [in/out] RFE_ERROR_FUNCTION_PARAMETER

\brief This function is intended to configure the direction of the signal to make use of the AC ATB bus based on the input source, from internal source to external or from external source to internal. This function make usage of 3SPI transactions \details In order to avoid that during switching from internal source to external or vice-versa both switches might end up being on at the same time, the function enforces an intermediate state where AC bus switches are both disconnected, before setting them according to the required configuration. This costs an extra SPI transaction. \attention In any case prior to use this function the AC IF Buffer has to be configure either enabled for RX and ADC inputs or disabled for external inputs, if not the function will disable the AC bus to prevent short circuits. Use rfeHwAtb_ctrlAtbACEnableIFBuffer() for this. \param [in] selectedAtbX: variable indicating which AC ATB bus to configure. rfeHwAtb_atbMaster_1_e selects AC1 rfeHwAtb_atbMaster_2_e selects AC2 \param [in] inputSource: variable to select the source of the input for the AC ATB bus. rfeHwAtb_atbSource_ac_Rx_e selects internal Rx as input towards AC1 or AC2 rfeHwAtb_atbSource_ac_Adc_e selects internal Adc as input towards AC1 or AC2 rfeHwAtb_atbSource_esd_debug_pins_e selects external Debug Pins as input towards AC1 or AC2 \param [in/out] RFE_ERROR_FUNCTION_PARAMETER

\brief Function intended to configure the AC signal that will be using the selected AC ATB bus, either from internal source or external source upon configured by selectedACSignal This function make use of 10SPI transactions \details When the AC IF Buffer is on, we need to enable bit 17 on the value (inputSource) to be applied to all registers. If the AC IF buffer is off then we need to disable it, this function takes care of this too The content of selectedACSignal has to be written as it is to below registers. 1. MID_TO_PWELL 2. GATE_TO_0V9 Not bitwise of selectedACSignal has to be written to 3. MID_TO_VDD 4. PWELL_TO_VSS We need to wait RFE_HW_ATB_AC_WAITING_TIME_GATE_0V9_TO_GATE_1V35_MICRO_S before writing GATE_TO_0V9 and clearing GATE_TO_1V35 5. Clear GATE_TO_0V9 6. GATE_TO_1V35 \attention Internal AC signal rfeHwAtb_acInput_Chirp_Vtune_ac_P_and_ac_N_e is not yet supported and it will cause the function to throw an error. This function also relies on the ATB AC IF Buffer state to discern whether selectedACSignal is only one channel or more channels( only in IF ADC routing) \param [in] selectedAtbX: variable indicating which AC ATB bus to configure. \param [in] selectedACSignal : chosen AC channel that will occupy ATB AC Bus when going from Rx to external ATB pins. Or chosen channel(s) to be use as multiple input signal(s) from ATB external pins into selected IF ADC(s). Notice that this variable is an uint16_t where 8-lower bits are dedicated to routing Rx signals from internal to external and 8-higher bits enables/disables the routing towards the IF ADC from external input \param [in/out] RFE_ERROR_FUNCTION_PARAMETER

\brief Function intended to connect IF input signal via selected AC ATB bus to the debug pins for validation. This function makes use of ??SPI transactions \details The direction in which the AC bus is used is going to be imposed by the selected input, based on this, the function internally configures the right BUS direction, IF Buffer enabling and signal to monitor/inject. Notice that the gain for ATB AC IF Buffer is set to its default (gain = 1) This function routes AC signal as 1. Enable AC LDO's 2. Enable AC IF Buffer on ATB 3. Set AC bus direction 4. Connect signal to use AC bus 5. Disable AC Pulldown lines \attention Internal AC signal rfeHwAtb_acInput_Chirp_Vtune_ac_P_and_ac_N_e is not yet supported and it will cause the function to throw an error. \param [in] selectedACAtb: variable indicating which AC ATB bus to use. \param [in] acInputSignal: chosen AC signal that will occupy ATB AC Bus either on downstream mode(Rx-to-debug-pins) or upstream mode (external-input-to-IF-ADC) \param [in] acAdcOptionalChannels: static array that complements acInputSignal with the extra channels that may be configured on ATB ADC to inject same external signal to all IF-ADCs. In that case, the expected content on this variable is an array of 7 elements mapping each one of the extra ADC channels where input signals must be routed to, if the required channels are less than 7, the array must to be filled with the value rfeHwAtb_acInput_NotUsed until it has got 7 elements. An example to enable to enable ADC1_I together with ADC2_I, ADC3_I, ADC4_I would be acInputSignal = rfeHwAtb_acInput_Adc_1_I_P_and_I_N_e; acAdcOptionalChannels = {rfeHwAtb_acInput_Adc_2_I_P_and_I_N_e,, rfeHwAtb_acInput_Adc_3_I_P_and_I_N_e, rfeHwAtb_acInput_Adc_4_I_P_and_I_N_e, rfeHwAtb_acInput_NotUsed, rfeHwAtb_acInput_NotUsed, rfeHwAtb_acInput_NotUsed, rfeHwAtb_acInput_NotUsed } Notice that in case the AC bus is being used for a Rx signal ( Rx-to-debug-pins) this variable is ignored. However since the variable is defined as an static array of 7 elements it has to be filled anyhow. acAdcOptionalChannels = {rfeHwAtb_acInput_NotUsed, rfeHwAtb_acInput_NotUsed, rfeHwAtb_acInput_NotUsed, rfeHwAtb_acInput_NotUsed, rfeHwAtb_acInput_NotUsed, rfeHwAtb_acInput_NotUsed, rfeHwAtb_acInput_NotUsed } \param [in] enable: variable to enable (true) or disable (false) the AC IF signal on ATB AC bus \param [in/out] RFE_ERROR_FUNCTION_PARAMETER

\brief Function intended to override the internal ATB ADC flag indicating whether ATB ADCs calibration/trimming has taken place is set to the value indicated on variable overrideCalibration. This function doesn't make use of SPI transactions \details This function is ONLY intended for validation for cases where the ATB ADCs want to be used without being calibrated. This function has to be used after having finalized ATB ADC calibration/trimming procedure. The function allows to overwrite the internal flag on ATB setting structure that indicates whether or not the ATB ADC has been calibrated.By default the flag is always false, it is set after ATB ADCs calibration has happened. \attention If this function is used to override ATB ADC calibration state, it is up to the user to set back the original state of the flag or start ATB ADCs calibration to restore its correct value; otherwise this can lead to use uncalibrated measurements of ATB ADCs \param[in] selectedAtbX : selected ATB where the overruling of ATB ADC calibration is going to be applied \param[in] overrideCalibFlag: boolean overriding the internal ATB ADC calibration/trimming flag that indicates whether or not the ATB ADC has been calibrated/trimmed \param[in/out] RFE_ERROR_FUNCTION_PARAMETER

\fn void rfeHwAtb_ctrAtbAdcGroundSingleModeSetter(rfeHwAtb_atbMaster_t, rfeHwAtb_muxVNegSeSel_t, rfeHwSpi_register32_t*, rfe_error_t* const) \brief Function to select what ground to be used on the ATB ADC only when working in single mode. The function performs a check on that, throwing an error if not set the single mode \details ATB HW allows the configuration of the ATB ADC ground via MUX_VNEG_SE multiplexer, this function enables this functionality. Thus this function will rely on having defined preivously the ATB ADC to work in single mode, via rfeHwAtb_ctrlAtbAdcInputSingleModeSetter(); in that case this function checks what ATBxMaster needs to configure and it sets the ground to be set in the ADC via the MUX_VNEG_SE. The grounding mapping can be found in atbAdcDifferential-Single-Mode-Pionout_v0p1.vsdx tab Pinout-Single-End-Grounding. \param currentAtbXMaster: ATBxMaster where the ADC will be configured \param adcSingleModeGround: variable indicating the ground to be used by the ATB ADC single-ending mode. \param pAtbAdcInputMux: register that holds all muxers (MUX_P/N and MUX_VNEG_SE) configuration and that will be modified accordlingly to adcInputSel \param RFE_ERROR_FUNCTION_PARAMETER \return updated atbAdcInputMux with the configured ground for single mode

\fn void rfeHwAtb_ctrlAtbAdcInputSingleModeSetter(rfeHwAtb_adcSel_In_t, rfeHwAtb_muxVNegSeSel_t, rfeHwAtb_atbMaster_t, rfeHwSpi_register32_t*, rfeHwSpi_register32_t*, rfe_error_t* const) \brief Function that configure the ATB ADC into singled-end mode based on the input towards the ADC ( indicated via ADC_SEL) and the desired ground indicated via variable adcSingleModeGround. This function does not make usage of SPI read/writes it just modifies the provided configuration registers accordingly to configure ADC in single mode and its ground. The function performs a check on whether single mode is set or not that throwing an error if not \details The configuration of single-ended depends on two inputs, the ADC input itself (ADC_SEL register) for single-ended and the desired ground for single-ended ( beacuse two can be selected depending on working case). This function is in charge of just setting the input of the ADC via ADC_SEL together with the muxer that routes the input (MUX_P/N) to be sampled. The grounding setting is delegated to rfeHwAtb_ctrAtbAdcGroundSingleModeSetter(), given that this function can configure the muxer that selects the ground (MUX_VNEG_SE) but also the origin of the ground itself, which may come from the MUX_VNEG_SE or from the MUX_P/N. In order to have a better overview of grounding for single mode please refer to atbAdcDifferential-Single-Mode-Pionout_v0p1.vsdx tab Pinout-Single-End-Grounding. \param adcInputSel: variable inidcating the input to be set in ATB ADC singled-ended mode ( this variable controls directly ADC_SEL) \param adcSingleModeGround: variable indicating the ground to be used by the ATB ADC single-ended mode. \param currentAtbXMaster: ATBxMaster where the ADC will be configured \param pAtbAdcCtrl0: register that holds the ATB ADC input selection and that will be modified with the selected input for the ADC \param pAtbAdcInputMux: register that holds all muxers (MUX_P/N and MUX_VNEG_SE) configuration and that will be modified accordlingly to adcInputSel and adcSingleModeGround \param RFE_ERROR_FUNCTION_PARAMETER

This function is in charge of setting the input of the ADC via ADC_SEL together with the muxers that route the input (MUX_P/N) to be sampled. Since the input is differential, the ground is fixed to vssa_1v8 via MUX_VNEG_SE for all cases. In order to have a better overview of pin connection in differential mode please refer to atbAdcDifferential-Single-Mode-Pionout_v0p1.vsdx tab Pinout-Differential-End-Grounding. \param currentAtbXMaster: ATBxMaster where the ADC will be configured \param adcInputSel: variable inidcating the input to be set in ATB ADC differentail-ended mode ( this variable controls directly ADC_SEL) \param pAtbAdcCtrl0: register that holds the ATB ADC input selection and that will be modified with the selected input for the ADC \param pAtbAdcInputMux: register that holds all muxers (MUX_P/N and MUX_VNEG_SE) configuration and that will be modified accordlingly to adcInputSel \param RFE_ERROR_FUNCTION_PARAMETER

\fn void rfeHwAtb_ctrlAtbCrossSwitchSetter(rfeHwAtb_crossSwitch_direction_t, rfeHwSpi_register32_t*, rfeHwSpi_register32_t*, bool, rfe_error_t* const) \brief Function dedicated to enable the cross-talking from one ATBSrcMaster to the other ATBDstMaster. \details This function will set origin ATBSrcMaster and destination ATBDstMaster signals to be swapped for ADC input, it does also enable the switch from origin ATBSrcMaster towards ATBDstMaster (enabling crosstalk).Finally, it sets ATBDstMaster configuration register from ATBDstMaster so that ATBSrcMaster input is forwarded to ATBDstMaster ADC and ESD_P/N ports. \attention This function does not enable 1. ATBSrcMaster source input: ATBSrcMaster source must be set via rfeHwAtb_ctrlAtbInputSourceSetter(), this done in this way to minimize a voltage increase in ATBDstMaster via cross-talk if the unit is not set in the right mode of operation 2. ATBDstMaster register read/write: this function does not reads nor write ATBDstMaster register via spi but expect it as an input. The reading/writing is left to the caller (likely rfeHwAtb_ctrlAtbInputSourceSetter()) where all reads/writes via spi are controlled \param crossSwitchDirection: variable indicating the direction of the atb's crossconnetion, from atb1 to atb2 or viceversa \param pAtbSrcDcSwitches0Reg: configuration register to enable cross-talk from the source ATB, called ATBSrcMaster \param pAtbDstDcSwitches0Reg: configuration register to enable cross-talk from the source ATB, called ATBDstMaster \param setOnOrOff: enable (true) or disable(false) cross-talking in provided config register \param RFE_ERROR_FUNCTION_PARAMETER

\fn void rfeHwAtb_ctrlAtbInitialize(rfeHwAtb_atb*, rfe_error_t* const) \brief Function to initialize the ATB into the right mode of operation dependinding on what functionality needs to be enabled. This function indicates the ATB initialization for the different modes in which ATB can work \detail The foreseen mode of operations are the following Not set : ATB is has all switches disabled IP DC usage: ATB is configured to route DC input into ATB-ADC IP AC usage: ATB is configured to route AC input into ATB-ADC External Voltage Trimming: ATB is configured to route its external voltage source(on OTP port) as input to ATB1Master, into ATB1Master ADC, and via cross-talking into other ATB2Master ADC as well as ATB2Master external output (OTP) External Current Trimming: ATB is configure to route its external current source (on OTP port) as input to ATB1Master ADC. This mode shall enable the Trimming resistor to convert current input into voltage to be measured by the ADC. Internal Current Trimming: ATB is configure to route its internal current source (on DC port) as input to ATB1Master ADC. This mode shall enable the Trimming resistor to convert current input into voltage to be measured by the ADC. \param currentIdModule \param currentModeOfOperation \param currentAtbXMaster \param adcSamplingRate \param adcAveragingMode \param adcAveragedEnabled \param adcSamplesToAverage \param RFE_ERROR_FUNCTION_PARAMETER

\fn void rfeHwAtb_funcAtbAdcTriggerContSampling(rfeHwAtb_atbMaster_t, bool, rfe_error_t* const) \brief Function to trigger data acquisition via ATBxMaster ADC using continuous mode of the ATBxMaster ADC. This function will perform an SPI read and SPI write via internal call \details This function relies on having configured in advance the ADC via the usage of rfeHwAtb_ctrlAtbAdcBasicSettingsSetter(), therefore, sampling rate, number of samples to use, averaging mode and duty cycle are NOT set by this function. In order to ensure that the ADC is configured, it checks that ATB mode of operation and the averaging mode are set, if they are not set the function will trigger an error and not acquistion will be triggered. \param currentAtbXMaster: ATBxMaster whose ADC is going to be configured \param startStopSampling: flag to start (true) or stop ( false) acquiring data via the ADC. By setting it to false we effectively change the ADC mode of operation to MONO stoping the acquisition. \param RFE_ERROR_FUNCTION_PARAMETER

\fn void rfeHwAtb_funcAtbAdcTriggerMonoSampling(rfeHwAtb_atbMaster_t, bool, rfe_error_t* const) \brief Function to trigger data acquisition in ATBxMaster ADC using mono mode. This function will perform an SPI read and SPI write via internal call \details This function relies on having configured in advance the ADC via the usage of rfeHwAtb_ctrlAtbAdcBasicSettingsSetter(), therefore, sampling rate, number of samples to use, averaging mode and duty cycle are NOT set by this function. In order to ensure that the ADC is configured it checks that ATB mode of operation and the averaging mode are set, if they are not set the function will trigger an error and not acquistion will be triggered. Also the function is capable to block itself the required amount of time in MONO mode, to perform the ADC acquisition based on the configured sampling time and number of samples to average, in case the caller is not capable of. In this way, we try to ensure that the register will contain the correct amount of samples. In order to enable this feature the flag enableWaitForSamples should be turned on. \param currentAtbXMaster: ATBxMaster whose ADC is going to be configured \param enableWaitForSamples: flag that tells the function whether enabling internal wait loop (true) or not (false) \param RFE_ERROR_FUNCTION_PARAMETER

\brief Function to initialise the struct that holds the config of the ATB. \attention When booting ATB the values will be set to zero, this may be an issue for the ATB since atbMaster[selectedATB].atbIpInUse.id will be zero too, which is the address of the SPIM module. Therefore, if a new IP tries to connect to ATB after booting, ATB will try to disconnect itself from SPIM module, but it was never connected to it, it was the default value after booting. Hence, we force the initial IP ID to the SPIM and we check in rfeHwAtb_ctrlAtbConnectToIpModule() if that is the case, if so we know that we have booted ATB and we don't have to disconnect from anything. We do use SPIM since this unit seems not to use ATB unit. \details This function checks internally whether the ATB ADCs are calibrated or not to reset the correction factor of the ADCs themselves \param RFE_ERROR_FUNCTION_PARAMETER

\brief Function intended to configure the ATB in order to calibrate its ADC based on selected ATB Bandgap voltage This function make use of SPI transactions \details The steps taken within this function to configure the ATB in such a way are the following Step 1: Connect ATB to itself to calibrate the ATB ADC via the bandgap Here we enable the usage of ATB on SPIM ACC Here we enable the usage of ATB1_EN or ATB2_EN @ ATB_CTL1 needed to route bandgap signal towards ATB DC Bus Step 2: Select Bandgap output voltage and path for signal, this is step A for bandgap TODO: currently we use yellow one, we need to enable here the purple path too Step 3: Enable internal ATB to route bandgap signal towards DC bus, this is step B for Bandgap Step 4: Select DC switches to route IP signal ( in this case ATB Bandgap ) towards selected ADC. This is step C for Bandgap Step 5: Disable DC pulldown lines. Notice that this can be skipped if they have been set on the offToStandby \param [in] bandGapVoutToSet: ATB Bandgap voltage to be set for calibration of the ATB ADC \param [in/out] RFE_ERROR_FUNCTION_PARAMETER

\brief Function intended to configure the ATB ADC selected in order to calibrate it This function make use of SPI transactions \details The steps taken within this function to configure ATB ADC are the following Step 6: Configure ATB ADC with the desired settings After this step the ADC is configured to perform: Step 7 -- to trigger a sample with rfeHwAtb_funcAtbAdcTriggerContSampling or rfeHwAtb_funcAtbAdcTriggerMonoSampling Step 8 -- to collect the sample with rfeHwAtb_funcAtbCollectSamples Recommended settings from designer for ATB ADC are these: rfeHwAtb_adcGainMode_t adcGainMode = rfeHwAtb_adcGainMode_normal_e; rfeHwAtb_adcEndMode_t adcEndToSet = rfeHwAtb_adcEndMode_single_e; rfeHwAtb_adcFclk_t adcSamplingRate = rfeHwAtb_adcSamplingRate_5M_e; rfeHwAtb_adcDutyCycle_t adcDutyCycle = rfeHwAtb_adcDutyCycle_50_e; rfeHwAtb_adcInner_Sel_In_t adcInputSel = rfeHwAtb_adcInner_Sel_In_0;// ADC_SEL=0x00 imposes MUX_P=0x02 rfeHwAtb_adcInputMuxer_VNeg_SE_Selector_t adcSingleModeGround = rfeHwAtb_adcInputMuxer_VNeg_SE_Selector_vssa_1v8_e; \attention The ATB ADC gain can be changed on this function, but this would imply reconfiguring the ADC with the same parameters only to change the gain. Hence, function rfeHwAtb_ctrlAdcGainModeSetter() can be used to just change the ATB ADC gain mode. \param [in] selectedAtbX: variable holding the ATB ADC to be configured \param [in] adcSettings: rfeHwAtb_adcSettings_t structure holding the settings to be configured for the ATB ADC. The parameters that are going to be taking for the structure are below ones, other values are ignored in this function adcSettings.adcCurrentSamplingRate adcSettings.adcCurrentDutyCycle adcSettings.adcAverageEnabled adcSettings.adcAverageMode adcSettings.adcSamplesToAverage adcSettings.adcInputGain \param [in\out] RFE_ERROR_FUNCTION_PARAMETER

\brief Function intended to restore ATB configuration to default mode after having performed ATB ADC calibration via ATB bandgap This function make use of SPI transactions \details These function performs the following steps Step 9: Disable DC pulldown lines Step 10: Disable internal ATB to route bandgap signal towards DC bus, this is step B for Bandgap Step 11: Select DC switches to route IP signal ( in this case ATB Bandgap ) towards selected ADC. This is step C for Bandgap Step 12: Set Bandgap output voltage to normal again Step 12: Check whether DIV2 mode is enabled,if so, disable it Step 14: Disconnect the use of ATB from bandgap \param [in\out] RFE_ERROR_FUNCTION_PARAMETER

\brief Function intended to enable or disable internal ATB differential buffer and associated divider This function does not make use of SPI transactions \param [in] useDifferentialBuffer: boolean indicating whether or not to enable the internal ATB differential buffer \param [in] useDividerMode: boolean indicating whether or not to enable voltage divided of the internal ATB differential buffer \param [in] selectedAtbX: variable holding in which ATB input differential buffer would be enabled \param [in] atbCtlZero: atbCtl0 register content which will be updated with internal ATB differential buffer settings \param [in\out] RFE_ERROR_FUNCTION_PARAMETER \return rfeHwSpi_register32_t a containing atbCtl0 register content with updated internal ATB differential buffer settings

\brief Function intended to enable the routing of bandgap voltage towards ATB DC bus via the internal ATB submodule \attention The enabling/disabling of ATBx_EN bit located ATB_CTL1 is delegated to rfeHwAtb_funcBandGapConnectCalibration()/rfeHwAtb_funcBandGapDisconnectCalibration() to ensure atomic functionality \param [in] enableBandgapInput: boolean indicating whether or not enable the bandgap voltage towards ATB DC bus \param [in] useDifferentialBuffer: boolean indicating whether make use of internal ATB differential buffer or not \param [in] selectedAtbX: variable holding in which ATB input differential buffer would be enabled \param [in] valueVss: variable holding which Vss has to be used for internal ATB submodule, by default is recommended rfeHwAtb_submoduleAtb_vss_disabled_e \param [in/out] RFE_ERROR_FUNCTION_PARAMETER

\brief Function dedicated to change ATB ADC's gain between normal mode or div2 mode. This function makes use of 2SPI transactions \attention When setting the gain in DIV2 mode and sampling rate is higher than 2.5MSps the Duty Cycle has to be set to 75%. The function will set this automatically in case that the configuration hasn't been updated after calling to rfeHwAtb_ctrlAtbAdcBasicSettingsSetter() \param [in] selectedAtbX: ATB where the ADC gain will be configured \param [in] adcGainMode: enum indicating normal vs div2 gain mode \param [in/out] RFE_ERROR_FUNCTION_PARAMETER

\brief Function that configure the ATB ADC into singled-end mode based on the input towards the ADC ( indicated via ADC_SEL ) and the desired ground indicated via variable adcSingleModeGround. This function does not make use of SPI read/writes it just modifies the input configuration registers( pAtbAdcCtrl,pAtbAdcInputMux ) accordingly to configure ADC in single mode and its ground. The caller of this function is rfeHwAtb_ctrlAtbAdcModeSetter(). The function performs a check on whether single mode is set or not that throwing an error if not \details The configuration of single-ended depends on two inputs, the ADC input itself ( ADC_SEL register ) for single-ended and the desired ground for single-ended ( because two can be selected depending on working case ). This function is in charge of just setting the input of the ADC via ADC_SEL together with the muxer that routes the input (MUX_P/N) to be sampled. The grounding setting is delegated to rfeHwAtb_ctrAtbAdcGroundSingleModeSetter(), given that this function can configure the muxer that selects the ground (MUX_VNEG_SE) but also the origin of the ground itself, which may come from the MUX_VNEG_SE or from the MUX_P/N. In order to have a better overview of grounding for single mode please refer to ATB SW Unit ConfigurationvX.pptx tab Pinout-Single-End-Grounding. \param [in] adcInputSel: variable indicating the input to be set in ATB ADC singled-ended mode ( this variable controls directly ADC_SEL ) \param [in] adcSingleModeGround: variable indicating the ground to be used by the ATB ADC single-ended mode. \param [in] selectedAtbX: ATB where the ADC will be configured \param [in/out] pAtbAdcCtrl: register that holds the ATB ADC input selection and that will be modified with the selected input for the ADC \param [in/out] pAtbAdcInputMux: register that holds all muxers ( MUX_P/N and MUX_VNEG_SE ) configuration and that will be modified accordingly to adcInputSel and adcSingleModeGround \param [in/out] RFE_ERROR_FUNCTION_PARAMETER

\brief Function that configure the ATB ADC into differential-end mode based on the input towards the ADC ( indicated via ADC_SEL). This function does not make use of SPI read/writes it just modifies the input configuration registers(pAtbAdcCtrl and pAtbAdcInputMux) accordingly to configure ADC in differential mode. The caller of this function is rfeHwAtb_ctrlAtbAdcModeSetter(). \details The configuration of differential-ended depends only on ADC input itself (ADC_SEL register). This function is in charge of setting the input of the ADC via ADC_SEL together with the muxers that route the input (MUX_P/N) to be sampled. Since the input is differential, the ground is fixed to vssa_1v8 via MUX_VNEG_SE for all cases. In order to have a better overview of pin connection in differential mode please refer to ATB SW Unit ConfigurationvX.pptx tab Pinout-Differential-End-Grounding. \param [in] selectedAtbX: ATB where the ADC will be configured \param [in] adcInputSel: variable indicating the input to be set in ATB ADC differentail-ended mode ( this variable controls directly ADC_SEL) \param [in/out] pAtbAdcCtrl: register that holds the ATB ADC input selection and that will be modified with the selected input for the ADC \param [in/out] pAtbAdcInputMux: register that holds all muxers (MUX_P/N and MUX_VNEG_SE) configuration and that will be modified accordingly to adcInputSel \param [in/out] RFE_ERROR_FUNCTION_PARAMETER

\brief Calibration dedicated function to enabled/disable BIST BUF + BIST RC filter and set bandGap voltage. This function makes use of 3SPI transactions for standard ATB powering up and 4SPI for Calibration process. \details This function in intended to Calibration usage in order to calibrate the ATB bandgap. The tasks here carried out are bandgap output voltage setup, BIST BUF and RC filter enabling/disabling. However, since some of the tasks are common too for the standard power up of the ATB, this function will be used there to set the bandgap output voltage to 0V. This function can work in two ways depending on who is using it a. For Calibration: readRegViaSPI and disableBistRCfilter have always needed to be set to true. Then the function will do 1. Read the bandgap configuration register 2. Disable the BIST RC filter 3. Enable BIST BUF 4. Wait for bandgap to be settled 5. Enable BIST RC filter and BG RC filter back In this situation the function makes use of 4 SPI transactions b. For normal power up of ATB : readRegViaSPI and disableBistRCfilter have always needed to be set to false, this function is used to set the bandgap output voltage, but we don't read the bandgap configuration register because that is taken care on rfeHwAtb_ctrlAtbBandGapDefaultMode(); thus, we can save SPI transactions. However, we need to provide the previously read bandgap configuration on variable atbbandgapRegIn, so that this function update its content with 1. Disable the BIST RC filter 2. Enable BIST BUF 3. Wait for bandgap to be settled 4. Enable BG RC filter back In this scenario the function makes use of 3 SPI transactions As reminder on how to Power On ATB the general steps are illustrated below. Steps 1,2 and 3 are being performed within rfeHwAtb_ctrlAtbPowerOn(): 1. Read PON register config and bandgap register config. TODO, if this step were handled in the Power Manager it should be removed from this function 2. Enable Level shifters . TODO,if this step were handled in the Power Manager it should be removed from this function 3. Enable ADC Level shifters. TODO,if this step were handled in the Power Manager it should be removed from this function The steps are being performed within this function: 4. Enable BandGap, set standard operation configuration bits, set on rfeHwAtb_ctrlAtbBandGapDefaultMode() The steps are being performed within this function: 4. Set BandGap output and disable BandGap RC filter, disable BIST RC filter 5. Wait till bandgap flag is acknowledged 6. Re-enable BIST RC filter and bandgap RC filter \attention This function requires a prior call to rfeHwAtb_funcBandGapConnectCalibration() to pre-configure ATB connections towards inner bandgap \param [in] bandGapVoutToSet bandgap output voltage to be set \param [in] disableBistRCfilter variable to control whether to disable BIST RC filter ( true ) or not ( false ) \param [in] readRegViaSPI variable to indicate whether perform an SPI read on bandgap control register. Always true for Calibration and false for normal ATB power up ( see details above ) \param [in] atbbandgapRegIn variable only used if readRegViaSPI set to ( false ) containing a previous read bandgap control register configuration to be updated and written. Only used in normal power up of ATB. \param [in/out] RFE_ERROR_FUNCTION_PARAMETER

\brief This function for calibration is intended to enable ATB capabilities to calibrate ATB inner bandgap via ATB ADC's. This function make usage of 4 SPI transactions in SPI optimised mode or 10 SPI transactions in memory optimised mode \details This function perform the following three requested tasks 1.It will enable the reset of the ATB ADC's correction factors 2.It will select the appropriated nodes (via ATB_SEL register) within ATB to connect bandgap output towards the ADC's 3.Upon normal operation of bandgap is started properly ATB will be configured with settings of 2 3.1 Using optimised version for SPI -> 4SPI 3.2 Using optimised version for memory -> 10SPI/6SPI( if disconnection of other IP on ATB needs to happen) \attention After this function has been called, rfeHwAtb_ctrlAtbBandGapOutputForCalibration() can be used as many times as desired for calibration. Also, once the calibration procedure has concluded, this function should call rfeHwAtb_funcBandGapDisconnectCalibration() set ATB configuration to default values. Thus the sequence of calibration should be 1. rfeHwAtb_funcBandGapConnectCalibration() : connect ATB to its inner bandgap 2. rfeHwAtb_ctrlAtbBandGapOutputForCalibration() : perform ATB bandgap calibration 3. rfeHwAtb_funcBandGapDisconnectCalibration() : disconnect ATB to its inner bandgap 4. rfeHwAtb_ctrlAtbBandGapDefaultMode() : restart ATB bandgap with default output voltage \param [in/out] RFE_ERROR_FUNCTION_PARAMETER

\brief This function for calibration is intended to disconnect ATB from its inner bandgap once the calibration process has concluded. This function uses SPI transactions but its cost depending on whether using optimised for memory or for SPI,see details \details Once calibration process has finished, all ATB settings must be kept for normal operation. Therefore, calibration functionality must call this function with that purpose and afterwards to rfeHwAtb_ctrlAtbBandGapDefaultMode() to set ATB bandgap with default output voltage Moreover,the function has two implementation aiming for a degree of optimisation 1. SPI optimisation : 2SPI transfer to disconnect ATB from inner bandgap + 4SPI transactions to set ATB bandgap in normal operative mode + 2SPI transactions disconnect digitial bus -> Total 8SPI transactions 2. Memory optimisation : 4SPI transfer to disconnect ATB from inner bandgap + 4SPI transactions to set ATB bandgap in normal operative mode + 2SPI transactions disconnect digitial bus -> Total 10SPI transactions \attention This function will disable the reset of the ATB ADC's correction factors \param [in/out] RFE_ERROR_FUNCTION_PARAMETER

\brief Function dedicated to enable requested optional channels on the ATB AC bus in case same signal is routed to multiple IF-ADCs This function doesn't use SPI transactions \details The function is internally use by rfeHwAtb_funcRxIfToExternal() being its goal to process the input array holding the channels into the bits associated to enable the gates to route the signal towards the IF-ADCs at ATB AC bus level. This function looks only for ADC channels, if a RX channel is set rfe_error_atbInvalidInputSource_e will be returned \param [in] acInputSignal: chosen AC signal that will occupy ATB AC Bus either on downstream mode(Rx-to-debug-pins) or upstream mode (external-input-to-IF-ADC) \param [in] acAdcOptionalChannels: static array that complements acInputSignal with the extra channels that may be configured on ATB ADC to inject same external signal to all IF-ADCs. In that case, the expected content on this variable is an array of 7 elements mapping each one of the extra ADC channels where input signals must be routed to, if the required channels are less than 7, the array must to be filled with the value rfeHwAtb_acInput_NotUsed until it has got 7 elements. An example to enable to enable ADC1_I together with ADC2_I, ADC3_I, ADC4_I would be acInputSignal = rfeHwAtb_acInput_Adc_1_I_P_and_I_N_e; acAdcOptionalChannels = {rfeHwAtb_acInput_Adc_2_I_P_and_I_N_e,, rfeHwAtb_acInput_Adc_3_I_P_and_I_N_e, rfeHwAtb_acInput_Adc_4_I_P_and_I_N_e, rfeHwAtb_acInput_NotUsed, rfeHwAtb_acInput_NotUsed, rfeHwAtb_acInput_NotUsed, rfeHwAtb_acInput_NotUsed } Notice that in case the AC bus is being used for a Rx signal ( Rx-to-debug-pins) this variable is ignored. However since the variable is defined as an static array of 7 elements it has to be filled anyhow. acAdcOptionalChannels = {rfeHwAtb_acInput_NotUsed, rfeHwAtb_acInput_NotUsed, rfeHwAtb_acInput_NotUsed, rfeHwAtb_acInput_NotUsed, rfeHwAtb_acInput_NotUsed, rfeHwAtb_acInput_NotUsed, rfeHwAtb_acInput_NotUsed } \param [in] enable: variable to enable (true) or disable (false) the AC IF signal on ATB AC bus \param [in/out] RFE_ERROR_FUNCTION_PARAMETER \param uint16_t variable holding the bits to enable or disable the requested routing channels towards IF ADC. This variable will be the content for MID_TO_PWELL GATE_TO_0V9 GATE_TO_1V35
